      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The historical record of the 20th century is a stark testament to the dangers of unchecked nationalism, making the risks undeniably severe. The rise of aggressive, exclusionary nationalism directly fueled the world wars and genocide. While some localized forms of identity are benign, the powerful, state-centric nationalism that dominates modern political discourse is structurally prone to authoritarianism and conflict. Therefore, the historical weight of its destructive potential strongly suggests that its risks far outweigh its purported benefits.",
      "source": "target",
